The Idaei Dactyli were the Servants and Assistants of the Magna Mater; Sophocl. ap. Lil. called Idaei from the Mountain Ida, where they lived; and Dactyli, from 〈 in non-Latin alphabet 〉 the Fingers, for these
Priests were ten, like the Fingers;
• ul. Pol. l. 1. they served Rhea every where and in every thing; as if they were Fingers to her. Stra. Diodor. ap. Cyr. Yet many affirm, that there was more than Ten.

                  Segetia, is the same, under another Name;
from Seges. Because she takes Care of the Blade,
as soon as it appears green above the Ground.
Plin. lib. 18.

And Lactura or Lactucina to Flora, presides
over the Ear when it begins to have Milk;
(Lactescere.)

Tho' Serapis, of whose Name we gave the Etymology before, was the God of the Egyptians;
yet he was worshipped at Greece, and especially at Athens, and also at Rome. Paus. in Attic. Amongst different Nations he had different Names;P • bl. Victor. for he was called sometimes Iupiter Ammon, Tacit. l. 20. Plut. de Osir. sometimes Pluto, Bacchus, Aesculapius, and sometimes Osiris. His Name was reckoned abominable by the Grecians; Porph. l. Resp. for all Names of seven Letters 〈 in non-Latin alphabet 〉 are by them esteemed infamous. Some say that Ptolomy, Tacit. l. 20. the Son of Lagus, procured the Effigies of him at Pontus, from the King of Sinope, and dedicated a magnificent Temple to him at Alexandri ••
Eusebius (in Prap. Evang. l. 4.) calls him the Prince of the evil Demons: A Flasket was placed upon his Head;Macro. in Sat. and near him lay a Creature with three Heads; a Dog's, a Wolfs, and a Lyon's between them. A Snake with his fold encompassed them, whose Head hung down unto the God's right Hand, which bridled the terrible Monster. There was besides, almost in all the Temples, where Serapis and Isis were worshipped, an Image which pressed its Lip with its Finger. Varro says that the meaning of this was, that no one should dare to say that these Gods had been Men formerly: And the Laws inflicted death upon him who said that Serapis was once a mortal Man.

